# Per-device Wi-Fi band policy, consumed by configure_wifi() in setup.sh.
#
# THIS IS A SAMPLE. The real policy file is machine-local and untracked:
#
#   cp config/wifi-band-policy.sample config/wifi-band-policy
#
# then fill in your own locations and AP BSSIDs. The real file is gitignored
# on purpose — BSSIDs are geolocatable identifiers (public war-driving
# databases map AP MACs to street addresses), so they must never be
# committed. If no policy file is present, every device defaults to 2.4 GHz
# (band=bg), the wedge-safe baseline.
#
# Why pin a band at all: the Pi's brcmfmac SDIO Wi-Fi stack can wedge the
# board when it ROAMS onto a 5 GHz BSSID (see configure_wifi). The blanket
# mitigation is to pin devices to 2.4 GHz. Two reasons to instead pin a
# device to a SINGLE strong 5 GHz BSSID (locking the BSSID removes the roam
# trigger — a stationary device never needs to roam):
#
#   1. Camera kiosks: 2.4 GHz is half-duplex and congested, so a live camera
#      stream (go2rtc) buffers badly there. 5 GHz restores the ~6x throughput
#      and low jitter the stream needs.
#   2. Bluetooth coexistence: bt-autoconnect polls the paired speaker every
#      15s (by design, for instant reconnect when it powers on). While the
#      speaker is off, each poll is a ~5s Bluetooth page on the antenna
#      SHARED with 2.4 GHz Wi-Fi — long enough to starve latency-sensitive
#      clients (e.g. snapcast's time-sync). 5 GHz doesn't contend with BT,
#      so the polling is harmless there. BSSID-locking also disables
#      wpa_supplicant's periodic full-band roam scans (~4-5s off-channel),
#      the other source of multi-second 2.4 GHz stalls.
#
# Format — one device per line:
#   <location>   <band>   [bssid]
#     location : the value from /etc/pulse-location (hostname is pulse-<location>)
#     band     : "a" (5 GHz, BSSID pin REQUIRED) or "bg" (2.4 GHz)
#     bssid    : AP MAC to lock to; mandatory when band=a, OPTIONAL for bg —
#                pin a bg device that hears several APs at similar strength,
#                where roam scans cause periodic multi-second stalls but the
#                device must stay on 2.4 GHz (e.g. a wedge-prone unit)
#
# Anything not listed here defaults to "bg" (2.4 GHz).
# Comments (#) and blank lines are ignored; whitespace-separated fields.
#
# NOTE: band=a entries hardcode a physical AP's BSSID. Pick a NON-DFS channel
# on that AP (UNII-1 36-48 / UNII-3 149-165) — a DFS channel's periodic CAC /
# radar vacate makes a BSSID-locked client drop with no fallback, and
# cold-boot association to a DFS "No-IR" channel is unreliable. If you swap
# or replace that AP, update the BSSID here; otherwise the boot-time fallback
# (pulse-wifi-band-fallback.service) reverts the device to 2.4 GHz so it
# stays online.
#
# Example entries (replace with your own):
#
# living-room   a    XX:XX:XX:XX:XX:XX   # camera kiosk on a non-DFS 5 GHz channel
# den           a    XX:XX:XX:XX:XX:XX   # BT speaker polling was starving 2.4 GHz
# porch         bg                       # explicit 2.4 GHz (same as unlisted)
# pantry        bg   XX:XX:XX:XX:XX:XX   # 2.4 GHz locked to one AP: stops roam-scan stalls
